40|$|In {{this study}} we examine how <b>the</b> {{perception}} of <b>layoff</b> {{as a violation of}} a psychological contract can vary depending upon one's perception of employer contractual obligation. We also investigate how perceptions of layoffs vary depending on whether one is focusing on his/her own <b>layoff</b> or <b>the</b> <b>layoff</b> of someone else. Survey results from 81 layoff victims reveal that respondents perceive their own layoff as a breach of contract more than they do <b>the</b> <b>layoff</b> of someone else. In addition, respondents who believe strongly in employee self reliance perceive their own layoff as less of a contract breach. Ideas for future research and implications for managers are discussed in our conclusions...|$|R
